<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870916-0089 </DOCNO><HL> MIT Gets ContractFor $415.6 MillionFrom Air Force</HL><DD> 09/16/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> GD ML WX MD NOC BA HRS LK ROK SMF GE GT LTAEROSPACE (ARO)DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF) </IN><DATELINE> WASHINGTON  </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Air Force awarded a $415.6 million contract to the Massachusetts Institute of Technology to develop advanced electronic programs for military aviation and other purposes.    The research will be handled by MIT's Lincoln Laboratory on behalf of the Air Force in Hanscom Air Force Base in Lexington, Mass. The Air Force said the MIT project is to be completed in September 1989.    In other awards yesterday, units of General Dynamics Corp. received Air Force contracts totaling $320.7 million for F-16 aircraft avionics maintenance facilities; F-16 support and improvements; development of materials technology; and development of technology for air support of ground forces.    Martin Marietta Corp. received Air Force contracts totaling $88.1 million for Titan IV space launch-vehicle production, facilities and services.    Westinghouse Electric Corp. was issued contracts totaling $81.2 million for F-16 aircraft radar production and improvements for the Air Force, and nuclear-propulsion research and development for the Navy.    McDonnell Douglas Corp. was given a $60 million Navy contract for FA-18 aircraft training equipment.    Units of Northrop Corp. received Air Force contracts totaling $50.2 million for pilot training services and development of aircraft manufacturing technology.    Boeing Aerospace Co., a unit of Boeing Co., was awarded Air Force contracts totaling $42.6 million for space launch-vehicle upper stages, materials research and development of satellite equipment.    Ocean Technology Inc. got a $37.2 million Navy contract for shipboard attack consoles.    Computer Technology Associates Inc. received a $29.6 million Air Force contract to support space and missile-warning programs.    Units of Lockheed Corp. won contracts totaling $26.6 million for development of aircraft manufacturing technology, materials research and space defense research for the Air Force, and electronic countermeasures equipment for the Army.    Units of Rockwell International Corp. were given Air Force contracts totaling $24.7 million for computer software, rocket-engine development and electronic equipment.    Singer Co. was issued an $18.6 million contract for F-111 aircraft equipment.    Units of General Electric Co. won Air Force contracts totaling $15.8 million for F-101 aircraft engine improvements and development of equipment for radar satellites.    Goodyear Aerospace Corp., a subsidiary of Goodyear Tire andamp; Rubber Co., was awarded a $13.8 million Air Force contract for training support equipment.    The University of Dayton Research Institute received Air Force contracts totaling $13.6 million for research services.    Dynalectron Corp. was issued a $13.3 million Air Force contract for aircraft maintenance.    N.I. Industries Inc. received a $13.3 million Army contract for munitions.    Bozell, Jacobs, Kenyon andamp; Eckhardt Inc., a unit of Lorimar-Telepictures Corp., got an $11.8 million Air Force contract for advertising services.    Harris Corp. received a $10.6 million Air Force contract for weather satellite support. </TEXT></DOC>